Examples

In all the examples that follow, we are trying to estimate a causal relationship between x and y. I think this is \(P(Y| \mbox{do}(X=x))\) NEED TO CHECK THIS

Chains

This represents a sequential path from intervention to outcome via a confounder (x → z → y). Can bias causal link between x and y if z is included.

Simple chain (no direct link)

chain_dag <- dagify(z ~ x,
                    y ~ z,
                    coords = list(x = c(x = 1, y = 3, z = 2),
                                  y = c(x = 1, y = 1, z = 2)),
                    exposure = "x",
                    outcome = "y")

ggdag(chain_dag) +
  theme_dag()

Independence: x and y are independent (conditioned on z)

impliedConditionalIndependencies(chain_dag)
## x _||_ y | z

Adjustment set: shows what adjustment is necessary to obtain the causal link between input and outcome

ggdag_adjustment_set(chain_dag) +
  theme_dag()

Simulated data - Equations

  • x: \(N(5, 1)\)
  • x ~ z: \(\beta_1 = 4\)
  • y ~ z: \(\beta_2 = 2\)
n <- 1000
x <- rnorm(n, 5, 1)
z <- x * 4 + rnorm(n, 0, 2)
y <- z * 2 + rnorm(n, 0, 2)
df <- data.frame(x, y, z)
pairs(df)

Model of y ~ x. If we ignore the confounder, we get the total effect of x on y. This includes any direct effect (x → y) and and indirect effect (x → z → y). In a simple linear case, the total effect should be the linear combination of these two equations. Here we have:

  • \(z = x \times 4\)
  • \(y = z \times 2\)
  • No direct effect

So the total direct effect via z is \(2 \times 4 = 8\). As there is no direct effect, this is the causal effect of x on y:

fit <- lm(y ~ x, df)
summary(fit)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = y ~ x, data = df)

## F-statistic:  3196 on 1 and 998 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

Model controlling for z. This removes the path between x and y and removes the apparent relationship. Now we only see the relationship between z and y. This is overcontrol: we’ve biased the estimate of the relationship in question by controlling for the intermediate variable

fit <- lm(y ~ x + z, df)
summary(fit)

Simple chain (direct link)

chain_dag <- dagify(z ~ x,
                    y ~ x + z,
                    coords = list(x = c(x = 1, y = 3, z = 2),
                                  y = c(x = 1, y = 1, z = 2)),
                    exposure = "x",
                    outcome = "y")

ggdag(chain_dag) +
  theme_dag()

Independence: x and y are not independent (even conditioned on z)

impliedConditionalIndependencies(chain_dag)

Adjustment set: shows what adjustment is necessary to obtain the causal link between input and outcome

ggdag_adjustment_set(chain_dag) +
  theme_dag()

Simulated data - Equations

  • x: \(N(5, 1)\)
  • z ~ x: \(\beta_1 = 5\)
  • y ~ x + z: \(\beta_2 = -1.5, \beta_3 = 2\)
n <- 1000
x <- rnorm(n, 10, 5)
z <- x * 5 + rnorm(n, 0, 2)
y <- x * -1.5 + z * 2 + rnorm(n, 0, 2)
df <- data.frame(x, y, z)
pairs(df)

Model of y ~ x. Ignoring the confounder gives us the total causal effect. Here, we have three effects at play:

  • \(z = x \times 5\)
  • \(y = z \times 2 + x \times -1.5\)

Now the indirect effect via z is \(5 \times 2 = 10\), and the direct effect is \(-1.5\), giving us a total effect of \(10 - 1.5 = 8.5\). Let’s see what the model says:

fit <- lm(y ~ x, df)
summary(fit)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = y ~ x, data = df)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -15.2030  -2.9979   0.0844   3.0120  12.1991 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) -0.34263    0.31139    -1.1    0.271    
## x            8.54880    0.02852   299.7   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 4.414 on 998 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.989,  Adjusted R-squared:  0.989 
## F-statistic: 8.984e+04 on 1 and 998 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

Model controlling for z. By controlling for z, we no longer can observe the total effect of x (overcontrol). However, this does isolate the 2 single paths x → y and z → y correctly.
